-- в”Ђв”Ђ KubeVirt в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$KubeVirt is an open-source, CNCF-incubating project that lets Kubernetes clusters run and manage traditional virtual machines alongside containers.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2017, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$KubeVirt Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$KubeVirt review: the open-source CNCF project for running VMs on Kubernetes, its architecture, live migration, and how it compares to alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$KubeVirt is an open-source project that extends Kubernetes so that clusters can run and manage traditional, KVM-based virtual machines using the same declarative API and tooling used for containers. The project began at Red Hat at the end of 2016 and was formally started in January 2017, prompted by the question of whether virtual machines could be run inside containers and deployed by Kubernetes, so that organizations with existing VM-based workloads would not need to fully rewrite them as containers to benefit from Kubernetes-native scheduling, networking, and storage. KubeVirt was accepted into the Cloud Native Computing Foundation as a Sandbox project on September 6, 2019, and was promoted to Incubating maturity level on April 19, 2022, and version 1.0 shipped in mid-2023, milestones that reflect its maturing production use. Since joining the CNCF, the project has attracted contributors well beyond its Red Hat origins, including engineers from Amadeus, Apple, CloudFlare, Containership, Giant Swarm, Gitpod, IBM, Kubermatic, NEC, NVIDIA, SAP, SUSE, and independent developers. Architecturally, KubeVirt extends the Kubernetes API by introducing new custom resource definitions, most importantly VirtualMachine, VirtualMachineInstance, and VirtualMachineInstanceReplicaSet, which let a VM be created, updated, and deleted using the same declarative, kubectl-based workflow used for any other Kubernetes object. Under the hood, each virtual machine actually runs inside a Kubernetes pod that contains a containerized QEMU process managed by libvirt, with the Linux kernel's KVM (Kernel-based Virtual Machine) module providing the underlying hardware-assisted hypervisor; a primary controller called virt-controller, running as a normal Kubernetes pod, manages the lifecycle of these VM resources across the cluster. A companion command-line tool called virtctl works alongside the standard kubectl CLI to provide VM-specific operations such as starting, stopping, restarting, and pausing virtual machines, managing disk images, and opening the VM's serial, graphical (VNC), or SSH console. Because VMs are ordinary Kubernetes objects, they integrate directly with the cluster's existing storage classes and CSI drivers for persistent, stateful storage, and with standard Kubernetes CNI networking plugins and network policies, so VM workloads share the same storage and networking model as containerized workloads rather than requiring a separate virtualization stack. One of KubeVirt's most important capabilities is live migration: a running VM and its memory state can be moved from one cluster node to another without interrupting the applications running on it, using a pre-copy migration process in which the source node streams memory pages to the destination while the VM keeps running, resending any pages that change ('dirty' pages) until the remaining set is small enough for a fast final switchover; live migration can be triggered declaratively by creating a VirtualMachineInstanceMigration custom resource or by running the virtctl migrate command, and is commonly used for planned hardware maintenance, load balancing, or responding to node failures. As a CNCF-governed open-source project distributed under the Apache 2.0 license, KubeVirt itself carries no license fee: it is free to download and run on any Kubernetes cluster with nodes that support hardware virtualization (KVM), and community support is available through the CNCF Slack and GitHub. Organizations that want commercial support typically adopt KubeVirt indirectly through a vendor distribution, most notably Red Hat OpenShift Virtualization, which packages KubeVirt with enterprise support, a management UI, and additional tooling; other Kubernetes platform vendors, including SUSE and various Kubernetes-as-a-service providers, have also built virtualization offerings on top of KubeVirt. KubeVirt's primary competitors and alternatives are traditional hypervisor platforms such as VMware vSphere and its VM-management layer, as well as other Kubernetes-based virtualization approaches; its key differentiator is that it lets an organization consolidate VM and container operations onto a single Kubernetes control plane and toolchain, rather than running a separate hypervisor stack alongside Kubernetes, which is especially valuable for teams migrating legacy, non-containerized applications into a cloud-native environment without a full rewrite.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '66cb57df-a72f-4b48-8e7c-dd2074ba5b6e';

